<font color="#FF0000">HELLO BONE CRUSHER MR. DUKE</font><br>
<tt>Mon Sep  1  0:29:12 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Mr. Duke, and others. Please do not use my initials in vain.<br>
I resent your message of exclusion, Mr. Duke, that this is a &quot;vet thing&quot; and no one else can &quot;B.S.&quot; except vets of the jungle.  Sorry, but that is not the intent of the founders of this site.  I am a vet of the street of protest, not the killing field of the jungle. <br><br>
I do not dis-honor the true warrior. I have nothing but respect for the horror and violence that my brothers went through, although lied to and misguided. True hero's emerged from those rice paddies carrying their brothers on their backs.  This site has taught me to respect that bravery. That bravery overcomes and overrides the politics of protest that I was raised in. But - It does not make a political wrong war right.  <br><br>
Many of you are bloody hero's, just for having survived the horrors of the jungle, but that does not make the war right.  That is the most important point I can tell to you.  Despite individual tales of bravery, and they are many, or individual tales of killing &quot;gooks&quot;, and sadly, they too are many, they do not wash away the political reality that the war was a mistake.  They do not forgive the politicians for killing 58,000 of my generation, and millions of others, whose crime it was to be born in &quot;the wrong side of town&quot;.<br><br>
Look around you on this site. We used to have many adding to the richness of the content. Vietnamese, Asian points of view, Donut Dolly's, Vets with PTSD, Vets without, but now, we are down to a handful of blood lusting and shoot em up types, and me.<br><br>
It is so easy to rally around the M-60 30 years later. It is so hard to go to the wall, or go to Little Saigon. Because of this site, I did both.  Can any of you say that.  This site changed me as much as the war did, only 30 years later. Can anyone of you say that?  Are you all so locked into your narrow thinking that you cannot think a fresh thought?  Can not any of you think about it from a larger point of view? You are warriors nevertheless. Warriors are a type of brave and personal behavior under fire. I do not doubt any of you were brave and heroic.  On a different level, however, it was for nothing. In vain. Sold out in Paris and Washington. A War that never should have happened in the first place.  It did and many of you were brave.  You can be brave, and wrong.  They are not mutually contradictory.<br><br>
Edward has reclaimed his Native American heritage and I am proud of him for doing that.  Silent Warrior remains a mystery, but on occasion, writes wonderful thoughts filled with pain and agnst. Mr. Duke writes about bone crushing hatred. Cook, ah Cook, continues his one sided &quot;tank in a china shop&quot; thinking. Man,he is consistent.  Hey Cook, I agree you are a crazy and brave guy, OK? Just that you were a hero in a wrong war.  Can't you understand that?<br><br>
Sometimes I want to go out in my back yard and howl at the moon, I get so frustrated with this new group of posters (not protestors). You guys are brave, but you refuse to think a bit deeper.  Take the step, it will hurt, but you are tough.  It is ok to be a hero, a warrior, a proud soldier, even if it was a wrong war.  Why can't you see that?  I guess until you do, I will be here, to be called traitor and commie, wharf rat and worse, but that is ok, I know I will prevail. I will prevail because history has already proved my position was right. My deeds were truly patriotic. My love of my country unbended, and unyielding. yes, I love America, for its good, its bad, and its unthinking. I would lay down my life for this country, but never, never, for the puppet government setup in Viet Nam, or for that undeclared war.  <br><br>
I know LBJ and Nixon should be roasting in hell, and they deserve that too, but I sleep the sleep of the innocent, without blood on my hands, and with a mind free of guilt.  Take your best shots, warriors, for I am a warrior too, just of a different type than you are used too.  Silent Warrior knows what I am talking about, warriors come in all colors and sizes, schools and traditions, levels and deeds.  It is the intention that defines the act, not the act that defines the intention.  Sorry if I lost most of you along the way.<br><br>
doc spatz
<p><code>-- Patriots come in all sizes and colors...  (doc spatz - true patriot) </code><p>


